text: This is gonna sound strange, but I fully believe in past lives.¬† As a person that has had a lot of experience with¬†tapping into¬†past memories, this movie reminds me of a "time loop" - one where through his sad experience, he relives a life that he has actually lived before, in the 20th century.¬† His love of all things WWII make me believe that this is so - that's not a coincidence.¬† The very same thing, with the same cast¬†of players, might have happened before (or, as I have learned through my own observations in my own life - in a past life, he might have been one of the attackers, and it was 'his turn').¬† It is through working to process the trauma and learning to forgive - that we finally kill the loop.¬† I CANNOT WAIT for this film!

text: This looks like a really good movie and I honestly look forward to seeing it when it comes out. Despite that, (true story or not), it's somewhat annoying seeing PTSD depicted with the same types of people (war veterans and those of the sort), over and over again. It creates an already growing stigma that people can only have PTSD if they're a war veteran when that is NOT the cause. Victims of abuse, harrasment, and people who've survived dangerous situations are just the tip of the iceberg when it comes to the number of scenarios that could lead to someone being diagnosed with PTSD. I'm tried of telling people what I have and them saying that what happened to me is somehow flase because 'im too young', or 'im not a war veteran so I can't have ptsd'. I hope the day will come when they show a movie with someone with PTSD that isn't a veteran, but just a regular citizen. (Maybe there is one, but I haven't seen any to my knowledge). Still can't wait to see the movie though.

text: It‚Äôs really too early in the day to be crying, but that‚Äôs what watching a Welcome to Marwen trailer will do to you. The upcoming feature film from Robert Zemeckis is based on a documentary, Marwencol, by Jeff Malmberg, which tells the story of Mark Hogancamp, who loses his memories after being beaten almost to death, and as a form a therapy (because he can afford no other), he makes a replica of a tiny Belgian village and populates it with characters that represent him and those in his life ‚Äî both loved ones, and his attackers.  Steve Carell plays Hogancamp in the Zemeckis film (which Zemeckis co-wrote with Caroline Thompson), and is joined by  Leslie Mann, Merritt Wever, Eiza Gonz√°lez, Gwendolyn Christie, Janelle Mon√°e, Leslie Zemeckis, Diane Kruger, and Neil Jackson. Welcome to Marwen opens in theaters on Friday, December 21st;   Academy Award¬Æ-winning filmmaker Robert Zemeckis (Forrest Gump, Flight, Cast Away) directs Steve Carell in the moving true story of one broken man‚Äôs fight as he discovers how artistic imagination can restore the human spirit.   The screenplay for Welcome to Marwen was written by Caroline Thompson and Zemeckis, while Oscar¬Æ-winning producer Steve Starkey (Forrest Gump, Flight), Jack Rapke (Cast Away, Flight), and Cherylanne Martin (The Pacific, Flight) of Zemeckis‚Äô Universal-based ImageMovers banner produce alongside the director. It is executive produced by Jackie Levine, as well as Jeff Malmberg, who directed the riveting 2010 documentary upon which this film is based.  "Welcome To Marwen" new trailer was released alongside  "Mamma Mia! Here We Go Again" "Christopher Robin" in Marcus & Cinemark Locations "Dog Days" "Crazy Rich Asians" "Alpha" & "The House With a Clock in its Walls"  If you saw this trailer read the Replies below

text: I am so so so happy they are making a movie like this! Super creative! And about an important topic too of trauma. I myself have many traumatic experiences that give me something that most people would see as PTSD(Being physically, emotionally and verbally bullied severely for 8 years, sexually harassed and touched at one point, witnessing domestic violence over and over again, witness to a suicide attempt, family members died, almost dying at the age of 4) so I am grateful to a movie that focuses on healing after traumatic experiences. I can tell Mark has some form of a PTSD. He's not only trying to rebuild his life, but face old wounds. And its adorable and very sweet that his town of made up of people who protect him. Many movies focus on bad events but they never discuss what happens after when, in reality, the aftermath is the hardest thing to bounce back from.

text: Welcome to Marwen... The movie was just plain weird. Steve Carrell is great but the directing was garbage. There is a scene that really ticked me off. Mark is in court about to testify about the crimes that have been done to him. It had potential to be a heart wrenching, sad, and emotional scene. Instead, Marks doll character ‚ÄúHogey‚Äù starts fighting nazis and Mark crawls on the ground avoiding the crossfire (bullets). The movie was more about Marks dolls then actually Mark. I feel like i saw more of ‚ÄúHogey‚Äù then Mark himself. Not about overcoming his fears. The movie felt boring, i had no care on what the Marwen characters had to say because THEY ARE NOT REAL. They said based on a true story, they forgot to tell me 2/3‚Äôs of the movie is dolls fighting.  The movie also left plenty of questions unanswered. When Mark is in Wendy‚Äôs house, he notices a photo of a young child. It says something like ‚ÄúWe miss you‚Äù or ‚ÄúYou will forever be in our hearts‚Äù. But We never know what happend to the child and why it is included in the movie. The movie also didn‚Äôt tell us more about the side characters. The women of Marwen are Marks friends. But we never really go deep into who the characters actually are. Next, The movie ends with Mark and his good friend (Roberta) going out to eat some sushi, thats it. Nothing else, do they continue dating, do they end up marrying at one point? Lastly, this is my biggest frustration: In the end of the movie the film does not tell you what happens to the thugs that beat Mark up. Do they get a long sentencing? Do they get life in prison??? You wont know because they wont tell you. This movie is very confusing, making you wonder if it is Marks fantasy or real life. There was no music that moved you, no emotional scenes. Unlike the trailer, the trailer felt moving and had a wonderful soundtrack. Im just truly dissatisfied with this movie.
